    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-27T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Kulangsu/157: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Amoy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVitty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Amoy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-27T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 27, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 27—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. I have conferred today with the Japanese Consul General, my colleagues and
                    the Chairman of the Municipal Council and it now appears possible that a
                    solution satisfactory to all concerned may be arrived at soon. During my
                    interview with the Japanese Consul General he agreed to drop his demand that the
                    position of Chief of Police should be given to a Japanese and appeared more
                    reasonable with regard to the question of additional Japanese police.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Embassy [at] Peiping, Chungking and Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVitty</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
